      "writtenOn": "2018-09-26T14:26:25Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I haven\u0027t done a good job explaining my methods here, relying instead on this (not very good) example task.  In PS4, I implemented nested steps.  In this model, the whole \"task\" is represented as one top-level step; if that step fails, then the task failed.  This allows more organization, eg. \"setup\", \"test\", and \"teardown\" umbrella steps which in some imaginary UI could be collapsed and hidden when their results are success, so that we only have to look at the interesting parts.  We could call the top-level step something else, but I like that it\u0027s \"just another\" step.  A very simple (degenerate?) task could be one single, top-level step.\n\nI\u0027ve been aiming for a framework that is basically an annotated Go program.  Basically, anything between Step.Start() and Step.Done() is part of that step.  What you describe is more strongly structured and more of a pipeline approach.  I think there are pros and cons of each, but one thing I like about my approach is that we can easily reuse Go code that we\u0027ve already written for our servers.  Another benefit is that, to some extent it\u0027s \"opt-in\", ie. if I forget to use sub-steps or decide not to, all of my work just gets attributed to the parent step.  So our generated list of steps can be as detailed as we want it.",
      "parentUuid": "2e8d80bc_2973686e",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 32,
        "startChar": 1,
        "endLine": 32,
        "endChar": 38
      },
      "revId": "c60b66be01c56abe7082aeeb8191367c5822272a",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
